-- 19-code-generator-with-proof.cell
-- Takes a spec ("binary search on sorted array, returns index or -1").
-- Generates code. Generates property tests. Runs tests (simulated).
-- If fail: analyze, rewrite, retest. If pass: generate proof sketch.
-- Oracle validates proof.
--
-- Tests: proof-carrying computation, ‚äĘ‚ąė evolution loop, ‚äĘ= crystallized
--        verifiers, oracle-gated code generation, ¬ß quotation for code-as-data
--
-- Demonstrates Cell's killer pattern: LLM generates (NP), verifier checks (P).

‚äĘ spec
  given description ‚Č° "binary search on sorted array, returns index or -1"
  given signature ‚Č° "binary_search(arr: int[], target: int) -> int"
  given preconditions ‚Č° "arr is sorted in ascending order, no duplicates"
  yield description, signature, preconditions

  ‚ä® description specifies the algorithm, input, and output
  ‚ä® signature has typed parameters and return type
  ‚ä® preconditions constrain the input space

‚äĘ generate-code
  given spec‚Üídescription
  given spec‚Üísignature
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  yield ¬ßimplementation, code-text

  ‚ąī Write a correct implementation of ¬ęspec‚Üísignature¬Ľ that satisfies:
    ¬ęspec‚Üídescription¬Ľ
    Preconditions: ¬ęspec‚Üípreconditions¬Ľ

    Use a standard binary search algorithm. Return the 0-based index of
    ¬ętarget¬Ľ in ¬ęarr¬Ľ, or -1 if not found. The implementation must:
    - Use integer midpoint calculation that avoids overflow
    - Maintain loop invariant: target is in arr[lo..hi] if present
    - Terminate when lo > hi (not found) or arr[mid] == target (found)

    Output the code as a Cell ‚äĘ= expression.

  ‚ä® code-text contains a loop or recursive structure
  ‚ä® code-text returns -1 for not-found case
  ‚ä® code-text uses integer division for midpoint

‚äĘ generate-property-tests
  given spec‚Üísignature
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  given spec‚Üídescription
  yield test-cases[], properties[]

  ‚ąī Generate property-based test cases for ¬ęspec‚Üísignature¬Ľ.

    Properties to test:
    1. Found element: if target in arr, result is its index
    2. Not found: if target not in arr, result is -1
    3. Boundary: target at first position, last position
    4. Single element: array of size 1
    5. Empty array: result must be -1
    6. Midpoint correctness: target at exact midpoint

    For each property, generate 2-3 concrete test cases with
    { input-arr, input-target, expected-output }.

  ‚ä® length(test-cases) ‚Č• 10
  ‚ä® properties covers found, not-found, boundary, and edge cases
  ‚ä® each test-case has input-arr (sorted), input-target, and expected-output

‚äĘ run-tests
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  given generate-property-tests‚Üítest-cases
  yield results[], pass-count, fail-count, failure-details[]

  ‚ąī Simulate executing ¬ęgenerate-code‚Üícode-text¬Ľ on each test case
    in ¬ęgenerate-property-tests‚Üítest-cases¬Ľ. For each test:
    - Trace through the code with the given inputs
    - Record the actual output
    - Compare to expected-output
    - If mismatch: record the failure with step-by-step trace showing
      where the code diverged from expected behavior

  ‚ä® length(results) = length(generate-property-tests‚Üítest-cases)
  ‚ä® pass-count + fail-count = length(results)
  ‚ä® if fail-count > 0 then length(failure-details) = fail-count

‚äĘ analyze-failures
  given run-tests‚Üífailure-details
  given run-tests‚Üífail-count
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  yield diagnosis, bug-category, fix-strategy

  ‚ąī If ¬ęrun-tests‚Üífail-count¬Ľ = 0, output diagnosis ‚Č° "all tests pass",
    bug-category ‚Č° "none", fix-strategy ‚Č° "none".

    Otherwise, analyze ¬ęrun-tests‚Üífailure-details¬Ľ against
    ¬ęgenerate-code‚Üícode-text¬Ľ. For each failure:
    - Identify the root cause (off-by-one, wrong comparison, overflow, etc.)
    - Categorize the bug
    - Propose a specific fix (which line, what change)

  ‚ä® if run-tests‚Üífail-count = 0 then diagnosis = "all tests pass"
  ‚ä® if run-tests‚Üífail-count > 0 then fix-strategy describes a concrete code change
  ‚ä® bug-category ‚ąą {"none", "off-by-one", "wrong-comparison", "overflow", "logic-error", "boundary-error"}

‚äĘ rewrite-code
  given analyze-failures‚Üídiagnosis
  given analyze-failures‚Üífix-strategy
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  given run-tests‚Üífailure-details
  yield ¬ßimplementation', code-text', changed-lines[]

  ‚ąī If ¬ęanalyze-failures‚Üídiagnosis¬Ľ = "all tests pass", output
    code-text' ‚Č° ¬ęgenerate-code‚Üícode-text¬Ľ unchanged.

    Otherwise, apply ¬ęanalyze-failures‚Üífix-strategy¬Ľ to
    ¬ęgenerate-code‚Üícode-text¬Ľ. Rewrite only the lines that need fixing.
    Record which lines changed and why.

    The rewritten code must preserve the function signature and
    overall structure. Only fix what's broken.

  ‚ä® ¬ßimplementation' has same given/yield signature as ¬ßgenerate-code
  ‚ä® if analyze-failures‚Üídiagnosis = "all tests pass" then code-text' = generate-code‚Üícode-text
  ‚ä® if fix-strategy ‚Č† "none" then length(changed-lines) ‚Č• 1

‚äĘ‚ąė evolve(generate-code, spec‚Üídescription ‚Č° spec‚Üídescription)
  through run-tests, analyze-failures, rewrite-code
  until run-tests‚Üífail-count = 0
  max 3

  -- Each iteration: generate code ‚Üí run tests ‚Üí analyze failures ‚Üí
  -- rewrite code. The rewritten code replaces generate-code's output,
  -- then tests re-run on the new version.
  --
  -- Interface frozen: generate-code always takes spec‚Üídescription and
  -- yields ¬ßimplementation + code-text. Only the implementation evolves.
  --
  -- Termination: when all tests pass (fail-count = 0) or max 3 iterations.

‚äĘ generate-proof-sketch
  given rewrite-code‚Üícode-text'
  given generate-property-tests‚Üíproperties
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  yield proof-sketch, invariants[], termination-argument

  ‚ąī Given the verified code ¬ęrewrite-code‚Üícode-text'¬Ľ that passes all tests,
    generate a formal proof sketch establishing correctness.

    The proof must address:
    1. **Loop invariant**: State the invariant maintained at each iteration.
       (e.g., "if target is in arr, then arr[lo] ‚Č§ target ‚Č§ arr[hi]")
    2. **Termination**: Prove the loop terminates.
       (e.g., "hi - lo decreases by at least 1 each iteration, bounded below by -1")
    3. **Postcondition (found)**: If arr[mid] = target, then result = mid is correct.
    4. **Postcondition (not found)**: If lo > hi, then target is not in arr[lo‚āÄ..hi‚āÄ].
    5. **Precondition usage**: Where does the proof rely on arr being sorted?

    Express each step as a logical proposition with justification.

  ‚ä® proof-sketch contains at least 4 logical steps
  ‚ä® invariants includes a loop invariant referencing lo, hi, and target
  ‚ä® termination-argument identifies a decreasing quantity bounded below

‚äĘ verify-proof ‚Ėł crystallized
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíproof-sketch
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíinvariants
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üítermination-argument
  given rewrite-code‚Üícode-text'
  yield proof-valid, gaps[], verdict

  ‚äĘ= proof-valid ‚Üź (
    has-loop-invariant(invariants) ‚ąß
    invariant-references(invariants, ["lo", "hi", "target"]) ‚ąß
    has-decreasing-quantity(termination-argument) ‚ąß
    has-lower-bound(termination-argument) ‚ąß
    proof-covers(proof-sketch, ["found-case", "not-found-case", "termination"]) ‚ąß
    proof-uses-precondition(proof-sketch, "sorted")
  )

  ‚äĘ= gaps ‚Üź missing-from(proof-sketch, [
    "loop-invariant", "termination", "found-postcondition",
    "not-found-postcondition", "precondition-usage"
  ])

  ‚äĘ= verdict ‚Üź if proof-valid ‚ąß gaps = [] then "proof complete"
                else if proof-valid then "proof valid with minor gaps"
                else "proof incomplete"

  ‚ä® verdict ‚ąą {"proof complete", "proof valid with minor gaps", "proof incomplete"}
  ‚ä® if proof-valid then gaps has at most 1 element
  ‚ä® if not proof-valid then length(gaps) ‚Č• 2

‚äĘ proof-certificate
  given verify-proof‚Üíverdict
  given verify-proof‚Üíproof-valid
  given verify-proof‚Üígaps
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíproof-sketch
  given rewrite-code‚Üícode-text'
  given run-tests‚Üípass-count
  yield certificate, confidence-level

  ‚ąī Assemble a proof-carrying certificate for ¬ęrewrite-code‚Üícode-text'¬Ľ:

    Certificate contains:
    1. The verified code
    2. The proof sketch
    3. Test results summary (all ¬ęrun-tests‚Üípass-count¬Ľ tests passing)
    4. Proof verification verdict: ¬ęverify-proof‚Üíverdict¬Ľ
    5. Any remaining gaps: ¬ęverify-proof‚Üígaps¬Ľ

    Confidence level:
    - "high" if verdict = "proof complete" and all tests pass
    - "medium" if verdict = "proof valid with minor gaps" and all tests pass
    - "low" if verdict = "proof incomplete" or tests failed

    This certificate is the DELIVERABLE: code + evidence of correctness.
    The LLM generated the code (NP). The crystallized verifier checked the
    proof (P). The tests provide empirical evidence. Together they form
    a proof-carrying computation.

  ‚ä® certificate includes code, proof, test-count, and verdict
  ‚ä® confidence-level ‚ąą {"high", "medium", "low"}
  ‚ä® if verify-proof‚Üíproof-valid and run-tests‚Üípass-count ‚Č• 10 then confidence-level ‚Č† "low"

‚ä®? on failure:
  retry with ¬ęoracle.failures¬Ľ max 3
‚ä®? on exhaustion:
  partial-accept(best)
